To have a reliable significance test, model developers have computed Newey West standard error, which is valid even when the classical assumptions of homoskedasticity and no autocorrelation are violated. From the above table, it is clear that after estimating the robust standard error (using the Newey West estimator), there is no change in the coefficient magnitude, sign and significance with respect to the actual model (add reference to the actual model summary).  This shows that statistical inferences from the model are valid, and no autocorrelation and heteroscedasticity will impact the model prediction.


References:
1.	Newey, W.K., & West, K.D. (1987). A Simple, Positive Semi-Definite, Heteroskedasticity and Autocorrelation Consistent Covariance Matrix. Econometrica, 55(3), 703-708.
o	This seminal paper introduced the Newey-West estimator and is fundamental to understanding its importance in econometrics.
2.	Wooldridge, J.M. (2016). Introductory Econometrics: A Modern Approach. Cengage Learning.
o	Wooldridge's textbook explains the application of the Newey-West adjustment in regression models, particularly in the context of time series data.
